I"!(<p>There is a type of linear motion (LM) composed of some <a href="uniform-linear-motion">uniform linear motions</a> (ULMs), which is different than the nonuniform linear motion (NULM). Velocity function $v(t)$ of this type of LM is simply a step function [<a href="#ref1">1</a>]. Or it can said that each ULM is a boxcar function [<a href="#ref2">2</a>].</p>

<h2 id="boxcar-function">Boxcar function</h2>
<p>A boxcar function has only non-zero value $A$ over a single interval, which can be described with</p>

<p>\begin{equation}
\label{eqn:vsf-boxcar-function}
{\rm boxcar}(x) =
\left\{
\begin{array}{lc}
A, &amp; a \le x &lt; b, \newline
0, &amp; x &lt; a \cup b \le x,
\end{array}
\right.
\end{equation}</p>

<p>where the interval has lower boundary $a$ and upper boundary $b$.</p>

<oo>
